    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"394485\">suhr</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/.E2.9C.94.20Need.20help.20with.20the.20Natural.20Numbers.20Game.20Level.20le_antisymm/near/504188065\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130384\">Riccardo Brasca</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Need.20help.20with.20the.20Natural.20Numbers.20Game.20Level.20le_antisymm/near/504187113\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>please don't mix standard Lean with NNG, it can be very confusing for beginners.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yep, sorry for that (why doesn't NNG use the usual definition of <code>≤</code>?).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Because I did extensive testing with mathematics undergraduates and established beyond all doubt that they found the recursive definition confusing</p>",
        "id": 504196065,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741385963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"886569\">@Lisa</span> I agree that this level is very hard! For a start you don't do it by induction, in contrast to many other levels. Secondly the result is geometrically obvious: given two points on the number line obviously they can't both be to the left of the other one without being the same -- this is not a statement which needs a proof in a normal maths class so I'm asking you to do something which you've probably never thought about. The point of advanced addition world is to give you the theorems you need in order to get through &lt;= world and by this point you have to understand the difference between a one way implication (which you <code>apply</code>) and an equality (which you <code>rw</code>). So there's a lot going on in this level.</p>",
        "id": 504197625,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741386388
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/.E2.9C.94.20Need.20help.20with.20the.20Natural.20Numbers.20Game.20Level.20le_antisymm/near/504196065\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Because I did extensive testing with mathematics undergraduates and established beyond all doubt that they found the recursive definition confusing</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In this case one can introduce it as a black box with lemmas.</p>",
        "id": 504197817,
        "sender_full_name": "suhr",
        "timestamp": 1741386441
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How is this different to what I do?</p>",
        "id": 504198734,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741386696
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh -- you mean refl and step as black boxes? But with my approach you can prove these and the proofs are a nice introduction to how to use &lt;= defined as the exists.</p>\n<p>The other reason is that I've taught induction already right at the start of the game, as well as rw, and I really need an excuse to teach intro, apply and exact and then to practice them extensively.</p>",
        "id": 504200128,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741387230
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The difference is NNG definition is different from the definition in the standard library, so doing anything that does not exactly follows the game course would fail. With black box approach you can keep the usual definition and in the same time provide many ways to solve a problem.</p>\n<p>Insufficient freedom is my main complain against NNG (by the way, the Lean 3 version had more freedom because rules were less rigid).</p>",
        "id": 504200430,
        "sender_full_name": "suhr",
        "timestamp": 1741387354
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"This is ≤. You can do <code>refl</code>, you can do <code>step</code>. You can do <code>exists_of_le</code>, you can do the induction principle if you wish so. Good luck.\"</p>",
        "id": 504200705,
        "sender_full_name": "suhr",
        "timestamp": 1741387494
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I agree that deviating from the standard library is not ideal. However as I already said, extensive testing showed that the standard library's definition was not suitable for my goal, which is to get mathematicians using theorem provers, and that trumps everything else. You a have a computer science background if I'm not mistaken, and introducing these people to lean is completely different question and not one I am qualified to talk about. I can believe that for people with your background another approach might be better.</p>",
        "id": 504200893,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1741387578
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that even with the standard library the \"best\" (in quote since it is not 100% objective) practice is to ignore the definition of any notion, but to use the API.</p>",
        "id": 504202064,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1741388240
    },
    {
